This red-sauce Italian spot has been in the same space in Williamsburg since the beginning of the last century. The dining room hasn’t been updated since the ’50s, and the space is still filled with tuxedo-wearing servers who bring family-style plates of baked ziti and pork chop parmesan to big tables of people. If you haven’t been part of one of those big tables of people, it’s time you made it into this classic establishment.  The fact that this place hasn’t changed at all - despite Williamsburg’s transformation around it - makes eating here that much more special. The space still has old phone booths, the walls are covered in pictures of the pope and signed portraits of celebrities, and the house bread comes with foil-wrapped butter packets. When your server opens the wine and fills your glass to the brim, you may have flashbacks to your first visit to the city - when you went into a spot in Little Italy with a street sign out front that said “Best Italian Food in New York”, and you ended up spending two hours eating mediocre cannolis and listening to the owner’s daughter sing “These Boots Are Made For Walkin’“. But Bamonte’s isn’t sticking to its traditions as a gimmick. It’s just doing what it’s always done: be a welcoming place to share food covered mostly in cheese and tomato sauce with a group of people.
This spot obviously knows how to please their clients. Always with a welcoming approach. The food is fairly priced, always flavorful and clean.

Bamonte’s is a must go if you  are looking for a real authentic Italian dining experience.  I met my best friend and girl friend there at 4:30 PM on a Sunday in February. The dining room was busy so we started with a few classic martinis at the bar. We promptly sat down at 5PM. The hostesses that sat us was one of the sisters of the brothers that own it. She sat with us for a few to tell us about the 120 year history behind the restaurant. It was amazing!!  As for our meals, we started with a few antipasto dishes paired with red wine. For dinner we had meat lasagna, chicken parmigiana and veal scallopini. Each dish tasted as though my Italian grandmother was making it from scratch in the kitchen. It was delicious.  If you are looking for a dining experience as if you just stepped foot into a Martin Scorsese film, then you just go to Bamonte’s. Note, when we left at 7:30 the place was packed with people waiting at the bar to be seated. My recommendation is go early, relax and enjoy! You will have a great time.

I'd like to start by saying that I'm a veteran whose parents ran a funeral parlor when I was a kid - which means, yeah, I know what a bad day looks like - BUT despite that, I still know how to crack a smile. It cost nothing. And I get that smiling isn't a requirement, especially if it's not felt, HOWEVER efficiency IS a requirement in the hospitality business, so the next time I'm seated at a table and left to sit there for 11 minutes without a menu in a half empty restaurant that boasts more busboys than patrons, so help me God. The bus boys (though they played musical chairs with every table in the place, trying to fit a party that never arrived) weren't the problem though. The management and waitstaff just don't give a damn. When the food FINALLY came to the table, my family and I were fairly pleased. The sauce was okay. The table bread was low quality and somewhat stale ... actually now that I recall, just the gnocchi was good. Really good. Could've eaten just that. But the waiter was slower than molasses (seemingly intentionally) and just a cantankerous grump. We waited  a good 15 minutes for the check, and though my brother insisted on giving the waiter a nice tip, he really didn't deserve a friggin dime. He didn't even bring the food to the table. The bus boys did. He only took our order and brought the check. And for his behavior (which according to a comment from a few months ago is not uncommon for him) I blame the management. The hostess never came over to the table to ask how's everything. It's unfortunate because as a native New Yorker, I really like to support these old places. But nah. Addio! This wasn't my first time at Bamonte's, but it's certainly my last.

I probably should’ve realised my mistake when I asked for spaghetti pomodoro and was met with blank stare/confusion. I got the marinara sauce instead and it was watery and tasteless, pasta was al dente though! But honestly the sauce was a dead ringer for the Sbarro’s spaghetti I used to eat as a kid which for $16 at Bamonte’s is downright tragic. I went with a fairly large group and all our food was pretty mediocre: meatballs and fettuccine alfredo etc. Chicken parm was probably the best of the lot! The waitstaff was nice, albeit a little slow/disorganised

Tldr: Food amazing; service awful I came here for eggplant parmigiana and was not disappointed. The red sauce is good, the texture of the eggplant and breading was great, cheese tasty, and side green beans were excellent. The side potatoes were not good, but 5% of the the meal can fail and it can still be a great eating experience. The service was quite poor. I made a reservation for 4pm figuring that a reservation probably wasn't necessary for such an off-time, but polite to do. I arrived at 4pm and explained that the other members of my party would arrive in a few minutes. The restaurant was empty except for patrons at maybe three other tables. The man behind the bar said that my friends better hurry or else he would have to cancel our reservation. Again, virtually every table was empty. He explained that they needed our table at 6pm, so we needed to hurry. My friends arrived by 4:05. We were seated without a problem. The waiter handed us two menus for five people, explaining that they didn't have any more. We read the two menus and made our selections. It took at least 15 minutes of sitting with menus closed before the waiter returned to the table and took our orders. Is that why they worried that it might take us more than two hours to eat? The wait staff was clumsy and not friendly at all, often dropping bread, dinner plates, etc. on top of unfinished plates of food already on the table. I watched many other groups arrive and get seated without any hassle around 5pm. Perhaps they all had reservations AND were people who were known to the staff since they didn't check in at the bar or with any waiters, but that seems quite unlikely. It also took about 15 minutes after asking for the check to actually get it. I will not be back, despite the excellent food.

(Translated by Google) One of the most traditional restaurants in Brooklyn. They told us that the business has been belonging to the same family for four generations, more than a hundred years. The atmosphere inside the premises is very special, with assigned classic Italian decoration adorned with a multitude of vintage photographs with relevant figures who have passed through the restaurant. Do not miss this wonderful place, where even the toilets are worthy of a museum as you can see in the photographs that accompany my review.  (Original) Unos de los restaurantes con más solera de Brooklyn. Nos contaron que el negocio lleva perteneciendo a la misma familia desde hace cuatro generaciones, más de cien años. La atmósfera del interior del local es muy especial, con decoración clásica italiana asignada adornada con multitud de fotografías de época con personajes relevantes que han pasado por el restaurante. No os perdáis esta maravilla de lugar, donde hasta los aseos son dignos de museo como podréis ver el las fotografías que acompañan a mi reseña.

Decent red lead type food.  If you like old school Brooklyn, this is the place for you.  A no frills Italian American eatery, you just sit, order, and eat.  Bring your own entertainment; conversation with your friends, the waitstaff and restaurant will only provide you with delicious food. (Again, Old School Brooklyn)  All of your favorites are on the menu, and most interpretations were excellent.  An easy recommendation, if there ever was one.
